TY  - JOUR
AU  - Fajgelbaum, Pablo D
AU  - Gaubert, Cecile
T1  - Optimal Spatial Policies, Geography, and Sorting*
PY  - 2020
Y1  - 2020/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjaa001
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 135
IS  - 2
SP  - 959
EP  - 1036
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We study optimal spatial policies in a quantitative trade and geography framework with spillovers and spatial sorting of heterogeneous workers. We characterize the spatial transfers that must hold in efficient allocations, as well as labor subsidies that can implement them. There exists scope for welfare-enhancing spatial policies even when spillovers are common across locations. Using data on U.S. cities and existing estimates of the spillover elasticities, we find that the U.S. economy would benefit from a reallocation of workers to currently low-wage cities. The optimal allocation features a greater share of high-skill workers in smaller cities relative to the observed allocation. Inefficient sorting may lead to substantial welfare costs.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjaa001
ER  - 



